segments.text: This is December 26th at 1214 Orr Street.
My name is Bob Cornish and I'm interviewing Tom Niederauer in connection with the APA project, The History of Planning in Texas.
First, Tom, I'd like to ask you, would you tell us what your position is in Dallas and
how you came to get into planning.
Currently, I'm the program manager for the urban design and environmental programs with the planning department in the city of Dallas.
Initially, I was in architecture at A&M in the late 60s.
Became involved politically to some extent with the political undercurrents, I guess, at that time.
a summer in New York.
Came very involved with people in politics.
Enjoyed that end of life, I suppose.
Translating that into architecture.
I remember you from A&M.
My fifth year project was the Community Design Center to begin that.
Worked in the black community and worked with Joe McGraw.
He helped get me started on that.
about three or four weeks after I got started into it, Dolezal joined me.
He lost interest in his project.
So the two of us put it together for one semester and we brought in two junior members, our fourth year members at that time, to perpetuate this center.
In any case, we spent the whole year restoring a house, helping the neighborhood, raising funds, preparing a presentation to council for a mini park.
It's what I would call urban design now, not knowing at that time what urban design was.
Did you go to Washington?
Yes, George and I both, plus John O'Terry, I believe.
We went for that first meeting, session, convocation or something of community design center types, and that further instilled my interest.
interest, I guess, in the political side of architecture slash planning slash what I would now call urban design.
Saw a job in Dallas in the planning department because of their neighborhood planning program, which I thought was comparable.
As I mentioned to you earlier, we wanted to stay in Texas and then go on to New York.
This seemed like a good place to be for the time being.
I liked the metropolitan area and stayed away from Houston, so basically that leaves Dallas.
That's how we got to Dallas and how I became interested in planning.
I was actually hired not really knowing what I was doing.
I was hired as part of the initial staff of the urban design program up there.
Well, your project at A&M helped you, didn't it?
Yeah.
On Hearn?
Hearn.
Were you on the Hearn project?
No.
In my section?
I don't recall that one.
No, I bet apparently you were not.
No, it was mostly this community design center out here that got me turned on to the political or social side of planning and architecture.
But that stuck.
that had become involved in the urban design programs and Wei Ming Lu came and we began to put all of that together.
Robin McCaffrey, a very inventive person, he and I both started working in the planning department together and probably it was the association with Robin that helped me stick with that.
Otherwise I might have lost interest and we sort of helped each other get along through the earlier parts until Wei Ming came.
Who was the planning director then?
Jim Schroeder.
James M. Schroeder, Jr., actually, was the acting director at that time.
The mayor was Eric Johnson.
That was of some significance because he was a strong planner.
It was primarily through his Goals for Dallas program that he essentially mandated this urban design setup.
Johnson opposed Schroeder becoming the planning director
Johnson wanted to go out.
In fact, he was very interested in bacon out of Philadelphia.
He was a very strong design person.
That's where Johnson wanted to take us.
Schroeder won the position through a lot of in-house politics, I suppose.
One never knows exactly, but he was very developer-oriented and had made a lot of those associations.
And they, of course, still had a very strong influence in Dallas at that time.
So Schroeder won the position.
In fact, I think it was about Christmas 1970 when he became director.
Just, yeah, I see.
That's about the time you got there.
Yeah, I'd been there for six months or so.
But he was putting the department together.
Who was the director before Schroeder?
I'm trying to remember the guy's name.
It's Alvin Deyo, D-E-Y-O, I believe.
He had long since left before I, Schroeder was acting director for almost two years, I believe, maybe a little longer.
So Deyo had left in like 68, something.
I know very little about him, and it was, he was there for a fairly short period, I think, because Springer left in 63, four, five, now I've forgotten.
Okay.
Well, we're interviewing Springer and Shorter, too, so we can make cross-connections and all that.
Some of this information you may or may not know, and if you don't, we'll just skip over it because some of it can be done by library work.
Do you happen to remember or know when the first comprehensive plan was authorized for Dallas?
I don't know of any official documents
that authorize or are adopted a comprehensive plan in Dallas.
Now the attitude since I've been there is that our zoning maps, the maps are the comprehensive plans.
Essentially the boundaries indicate what's to be built where, but they are not comprehensive.
Well, Dallas has substituted zoning for
General comprehensive planning.
Right.
Well, I say that's the attitude.
I think that's the legal excuse, if we're challenged, that the city is prepared to defend itself with.
I've heard that.
Does Alec Bickley go along with that?
Well, now, Bickley's a former city attorney.
I know.
That probably came from Bickley.
I'm not sure where that attitude came from.
It was something that sort of floated around the office.
All planners come in and say, where's our comprehensive plan and why aren't we doing one?
For ten years.
And the new crop that's come in this year says the same thing.
We are working towards a comprehensive plan at this time with Shoup.
Schroeder put one together.
It wasn't a bad plan overall, accepted by the commission.
Don't think he did his politicking well.
And that's obvious.
It didn't pass.
So I don't know whether to blame him or not.
But it did not get through council.
And it became the platform for the mayor's race, which was a special election.
And that's when Bob Folsom came in with like 50.2% of the vote over 49.8% for Weber, who was in favor of it.
So the community is very split.
Bob Folsom's done.
very influential home developer primarily in the north part of Dallas.
SMUX, which seems to be a... What position was he running for?
Oh, the mayor.
Oh, and he was elected.
At that time, Wes Wise was mayor, resigned to run for Congress, and so there was a special election to fill the mayor's post.
Gary Weber, who was on the council, who was a stockbroker primarily, was on the council, resigned to run for the mayor's position, so that opened up another position on council.
So there were two positions open, basically.
And it was a heated race.
And somewhere in the neighborhood of a half million dollars spent.
When was this?
In 16, I mean, 75.
I believe that's when it was.
I have to check back exactly.
Adeline Harrison was on city council at that time.
And she became, in fact, the acting mayor during a short period of time.
This was after Johnson?
Yeah, yeah.
Wes Wise was a two-and-a-half term mayor after Eric Johnson, the half term being when he resigned to run for Congress.
Bob Folsom filled the other half, and then the last two terms.
But it was a heated race, and as I said, a half million dollars approximately spent.
the campaign and the issue was the comprehensive plan for Dallas.
It's almost an even split in the community and one never knows how the community actually feels about the comprehensive plan.
There were other issues, but it was interesting and being an optimist rather than a pessimist, I didn't look at
fulsome winning as a mandate from the public not to have planning, but rather it answered some questions that I'd had and that we'd had in the planning department for years.
This community does not want planning.
Here we had good evidence that at least half the community wants it.
So, as I say, being optimistic, that's been a driving force for us.
We feel a community is receptive.
So why is this pro-planning?
Why is
And Folsom was not?
All right, this was Weber and Folsom.
Oh, Weber and Folsom.
Gary Weber, who now is the county commissioner, county judge.
And is he pro-planting or otherwise?
I'm not clear on that.
Yes, yes.

Weber was on the council when Wayne Ming came to town, and he was our conduit for urban design programs for a couple of years until Adeline Harrison resigned from the planning commission and ran for city council, and then she and Weber both.
became a very strong alliance for pro-planning.
Environmental issues, the sign ordinance, historic preservation, those kinds of issues were passed during that period.
I'm assuming that because of him, that would explain the large budgets that were set aside for urban design at that time in Dallas.
Probably the largest budgets of any planning department in the country for urban design.
Yeah, at that time, it was quite large.
We had upwards of 19 people, I believe, at one time.
I don't know what to attribute that to.
Really, that was sort of a residual effect from Eric Johnson's days, more than anything, and just Wei Ming's ability to be a good bureaucrat and grow.
Tom, could you just give us a quick synopsis of the history of the urban design efforts in the Dallas Planning Department?
Yeah, quickly, from the Goals for Dallas program, it was apparent that the citizens wanted some sort of an urban design focus for planning.
From that, Eric Johnson
instructed his city manager, the city manager at that time, Scott MacDonald, to put together an urban design section in the planning department.
He, in turn, worked with Jim Schroeder, who was acting director at that time, to reorganize the planning department.
There were essentially two assistant directors, one for zoning and subdivisions and development plans, and so more than one for urban design.
There were some other program areas directly under Schroeder.
But the urban design position, being an assistant director, was an unclassified, I'm sorry, a classified position, meaning salary is a negotiable, not a civil service position.
Oh, yeah.
Yeah.
Schroeder proceeded to interview, advertise and interview for the urban design position.
And in the summer of 71, he hired a few people during that period, Robin McCaffrey and myself being two.
to help form a foundation for the urban design program.
And he hired Wei Ming Liu in the summer of 1971.
I'm sorry, it was about Christmas of 1970.
And Wei Ming came from Minneapolis, as I recall.
That's right.
Where he had put in place a pretty good urban design program.
He had started one up there, yeah.
Minneapolis is a considerably different situation.
good experience to draw to bring to Dallas.
But when he came to work in July of 71, and that's basically how we got started.
I failed to mention the Urban Design Task Force.
Eric Johnson instructed Scott McDonald to put together the Urban Design Task Force, a group made up of primarily the community's leading architects, design related.
professionals of landscape and planners as well.
I guess the leader of that group at that time was Jim Pratt of Pratt, Box, and Henderson.
There were others associated with it, but, and a few business people that were involved.
They... Is that Hal Box?
Well, now Box was not involved, but Jim Pratt was.
Yeah, it's Hal, that's the firm.
It was Hal Box, Jim Pratt, and
What's Henderson?
Phil Henderson.
An L box is now at UT Austin.
Right, right, same box.
But the Urban Design Task Force essentially helped us get our start in terms of organization of the division.
The AIA sponsored a booklet that the Urban Design Task Force wrote on urban design in Dallas, what it should be, some of the issues that should be addressed at that time.
And Wayming was essentially hired with their approval.
And so, politically, I'd say they helped us get our start.
They're still in existence and we're going through problems right now as to what their role is and so forth.
They're an advisory group to the city manager.
That's probably enough, I think, of that end of it.
Yeah, OK. Well, let's move on then.

By the way, I just want to ask you, in retrospect now, do you think that the urban design task force and the efforts made by the urban designers in the planning department have been productive in Dallas?
Definitely.
Could you cite some examples of the consequences of funding such a comprehensive urban design effort over the last 10 years?
You mean specific projects or on-the-ground events?
Yeah, if you could just name some things that have resulted from it.
I can think of one little short street right downtown that was cut through for a pedestrian street.
Yeah.

Well, you know, my attitude is that urban design has been around for years and years and years and years and years, but it's been done by public works departments or parks departments or sometimes planning departments, if they happen to have an architect on board, which most planning departments seem to do, and so forth.
So I think there's always been urban design going on in cities, but not an urban design focus.
It's been an implicit focus.
kind of operation, rather than explicitly Dallas.
Right, right.
Same in Dallas.
We'd had Stone Place Mall was essentially an urban design project downtown before we had an urban design division.
Not far different than Akron Street, a different kind of situation, but anyways, to say that we have had urban design in the past.
What, what, what Wei Ming did, he began to focus on the design aspects of planning and
including the community in making design decisions.
And, of course, I've learned a lot from him, and that's my philosophy, too, as to what urban design is, or at least a part of it.
So, a lot of community involved at the first was really important, and we had a sign ordinance issue that was in front of us when he came, and he used that very effectively.
to focus on the urban design program.

And we spent $100,000 for consultants in the early 70s, which was a considerable amount of money then, still is now, but national consultants, and put together a very comprehensive, progressive sign, set of sign regulations.
In addition to the sign ordinance, have there been any other
products or projects that have come about because of the urban design program in the De Plany department?
Well, that's what I was saying.
Wayne Manning had the ability to utilize his political base for spin-offs.

The interest generated in the community on the sound artist, for example, he used some of those same people to get the Historic Preservation Foundation through Chapter 19A in our zoning ordinance, permits us to do historic preservation.
I've institutionalized that since he left, and we're making it routine almost, and in fact trying not to call attention to it to some extent, to just build the program.
But that was probably the most important one in terms of the actual physical impact on the community, historic preservation programs.
Other specific projects, well, a spinoff of the historic preservation program is the establishment of the West End Historic District.
We now have a five block long mall being constructed downtown on Market Street in the center of the historic district.
combination, historic preservation and urban design project.
We did a neighborhood study of the Little Mexico area, El Barrio it's called.
Robin McCaffrey, in fact, did that.
And we got considerable improvements on the park in the center of that community.
That was another pretty significant project.
again through historic preservation, Wayming had a very sharp political eye.
We have a historic district in South Dallas, the black part of the city, for example.
So he's very aggressive politically at hitting all the bases, and I'm sorry to follow in that same vein.
some of the more significant projects.
Now we also began quite a number of environmental programs at that time, and we have a set of escarpment regulations for development of the escarpment along the southwestern part of the city.
And some of that stuff is just now coming.
Okay, let's proceed on then.
You're doing planning in Texas, right?
Not urban design in Texas.
Yeah.
Let's go back to the subject of the comprehensive plan.
I know that there were some planning consultants operating in the 20s in Dallas and so forth, and other people talk about those too.
You say that there is no really adopted comprehensive plan for Dallas at this time.
So we'll go on to some of these other questions then.
If your city does not conduct comprehensive planning, how would you characterize its planning style?
For example, does Dallas do advocacy planning by various groups, or does it do incremental planning as subjects are brought up by developers?
Does the city then respond to the ideas of other people?
Who takes the leadership role in
formulating plan concepts for Dallas and major development, I mean really major key development proposals?
I would say it's worked in all those ways at different times, depending on the leadership at the time, the planning director at the time.
Weiming Liu, again, had provided a lot of leadership in terms of progressive advocacy planning.
and gave Jim Schroeder the ability to become an advocate himself as the director of the department.
I would not call Schroeder an advocate planner in most senses of the word, but the ability to use the staff in that respect.
Mostly it's been a developer-directed city, perhaps.
That's a good word.
No, we don't advocate for the most part.
And that's, urban design was considered to be fairly radical for that reason, that we were pushing programs.
Has there been any particular identifiable group within Dallas that hired their own planner as their advocate planner to make proposals to the city?
On what scale?
That's... Oh, a neighborhood scale, even.
or for a large industrial complex or what have you.

Okay, on a neighborhood scale, I'd say only recently, but still they're very sketchy, more in terms of hiring traffic planners to fight street and thoroughfare decisions and those kinds of things, rather than actually laying out some sort of comprehensive approach to their neighborhood planning.
But certainly developers have, John Stimmons is probably the,
probably one of the state's largest industrial planners because of so much land.
Trammell Crowe does quite a bit of planning work.
He's doing the market center around Stimmins Expressway, built the Anatole.
He has a comprehensive plan for that whole area.
Does he share it with anybody?
No.
It's a backroom plan.
That's right.
He's doing the same with the northeast section of downtown, where we intended on putting an arts district.
And he has completely co-opted our plan.
So I would say Stimmons and Crow, and as a matter of fact, Stimmons and Crow were in partnership on a good bit of the development along Stimmons Expressway.
Those are the two key people, I think, in terms of individuals.
I think that...
Crowe did Park Central too, which is at the corner of LBJ and Central.
A huge complex.
Park Central?
Yeah.
Is that where the North Park Shopping Center is?
No, it's on further north.
It's at the next tier.
The Marriott Hotel's there.
I'm trying to think what's there.
A lot of office buildings.
There's a hospital there and so forth.
I think Marvin Springer knows quite a bit about Stemmons and what he was doing.
because that was during his era.
A lot of his work, yeah.
So we'll be able to pick up more from the interview with Marvin Springland on that.
Ross Perot is planning half of the city of Plano now.
Is that right?
Yeah, and they're going to annex a lot of land that he's planned.
It will double their tax base.
He's done some of that in Dallas.
Plano is apparently experiencing fantastic growth and also
escalating property values that are creating all sorts of problems.
They're creating a lot of problems for us, and we're not reaping the benefits.
I don't know if I answered your question, but we've been all of those things.
We've done what some would call a sign ordinance and some of those things, radical planning.
Certainly it's advocacy planning.
Well, radical planning I would typify as being almost advocating structural changes in government and that sort of thing.
We've come close.
But no, I'm certainly not that radical.
But the circumstances are hardly radical.
That's within the context of the status quo in terms of operational government.

Where it's radical, though, is that it's the first time that we've had something that seemed punitive towards a businessman as much as that because we have an amortization clause requiring them to remove signs.
That end of it was sort of radical from our department.
Well, yeah, but in terms of theoretical planning, it would be considered quite ordinary.
Oh, I agree with you.
Well, let's go on to, are you familiar with zoning in Dallas at all?
Do you remember when the first zoning ordinance was adopted?
I believe it was 1929.
I had done a little research on that before, and the key dates are 1929
Oh, God, I can't remember the next increment.
It seems like it was 1939.
I've forgotten the 30s date.
Okay, well, as you know, Texas state law requires that cities have an adopted comprehensive plan before they have an adopted zoning ordinance.
Does Dallas fulfill the state law requirement?
No, not to my knowledge.
We've questioned that internally before, as I mentioned.
There's been no taxpayer suits testing that?
Okay.
All right, now let's go on to the next question.
What administrative procedures and planning program elements does your community have for implementing community plans?
For example, do you have a department of current planning where they review all plat proposals and that sort of thing?
You're talking about for new development?
Yeah.
Development Services, I believe it's called.
I don't know what it's called.
I've changed the title every two years.
It handles all zoning and subdivision review.
The whole department, however, reviews all zoning and subdivision requests.
The entire department?
Yeah.
This is just... That means that you don't have any group within the planning department then that has as its primary task the formulating of long-range plans.
Oh, no, no.
I'm talking about only the...
the administrative aspects of subdivision zoning review.
Well, you said the entire department does this?
The entire department reviews those.
This one division focuses on that and makes up the dockets, for example, and takes them to the planning commission.
We do have a long-range planning group right now.
It's called Land Use and Public Facilities Division.
I see.
And we were working, intended...
We're working towards a comprehensive plan in three years.
And with this recent budget cut, that's been delayed.
We don't know at this point what we'll be doing.
I see.
But, yeah, we have a neighborhood planning group, which works at the sort of medium scale.
We have the land use and public facilities planning group, which works at the growth scale for the most part.
We have a CBD planning group, which focuses on just downtown, a very small group.
And then urban design essentially fills in the cracks on some of those things as well as advocating our own programs.
Okay, do you recall when the city first established the planning department?
It was established under the Public Works Department for some time and it was split off, I believe,
This is something that's going to need some checking, and Springer can fill you in on this.
I think Springer was the first planning director, and that's when the split was made.
I believe it was the early 60s.
I see.
Well, not until after the Second World War.
Maybe it was the 50s.
I'm not sure, to tell you the truth.
Well, we can check on that.
Do you know how many professional planners there are in the planning department now?
At this time, I believe there are 35.
We were authorized for 38 positions.
under this budget year with a cut.
The position to authorize the fund, the salaries weren't.
